Yes, this is exactly what **Git submodules** are for.

## How it works

1. **Your main repo** is a regular GitHub repository
2. **Subfolders** are submodules — pointers to specific commits in other repositories (your forks)
3. You can sync (update) each submodule independently

## Setup

**Add a forked repo as a submodule:**
```bash
git submodule add https://github.com/you/forked-repo path/to/subfolder
git commit -m "Add submodule"
git push
```

**Clone the main repo with all submodules:**
```bash
git clone --recurse-submodules https://github.com/you/main-repo
```

## Syncing only a specific submodule

```bash
# Update one specific submodule
git submodule update --remote path/to/subfolder

# Or cd into it and pull like a normal repo
cd path/to/subfolder
git fetch upstream      # from the original repo you forked
git merge upstream/main
cd ..
git add path/to/subfolder
git commit -m "Update submodule"
```

## Key behaviors

- The main repo stores a **commit hash** for each submodule, not the files themselves
- Each submodule is an independent git repo — you can push/pull/branch inside it separately
- Other contributors need to run `git submodule update --init` after cloning to populate subfolders
- You can update submodules independently without touching the rest of the main repo

## Caveats

- Submodules add complexity (easy to forget to commit the pointer update in the parent repo)
- An alternative is **git subtree**, which copies the code in rather than linking — simpler but harder to sync back upstream

For your use case (forked repos you want to occasionally sync with upstream), submodules are the right tool.
